          <h2>Tips for Beginners</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Start Where You Are</h3>
              <p>Honor your body's current abilities and limitations. Choose classes that challenge you appropriately without causing strain or injury.</p>
              <p>Remember that yoga is not competitive—your practice is unique to you and your body.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Focus on Foundations</h3>
              <p>Take time to learn basic poses correctly before advancing to more complex ones. Good alignment from the beginning prevents injuries later.</p>
              <p>Don't hesitate to ask teachers for adjustments or clarification on poses.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Be Consistent</h3>
              <p>Regular practice, even if brief, is more beneficial than occasional long sessions. Aim for consistency rather than intensity.</p>
              <p>Even 10-15 minutes daily can yield significant benefits over time compared to an occasional 90-minute class.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Listen to Your Body</h3>
              <p>Pay attention to how different practices make you feel. Your body will tell you what it needs—sometimes gentle restoration, other times more vigorous movement.</p>
              <p>Learn to distinguish between productive discomfort and pain. The former helps you grow; the latter signals potential harm.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Try Different Styles</h3>
              <p>Experiment with various yoga styles to find what resonates with you. Each approach offers unique benefits and teaching perspectives.</p>
              <p>Be open to discovering that the style you initially gravitate toward might not be the one that serves you best.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Dress Comfortably</h3>
              <p>Wear clothes that allow free movement and don't require constant adjustment. You want to focus on your practice, not your outfit.</p>
              <p>Practice barefoot when possible to help with balance and proper alignment.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-content-box" id="deepening-content">
          <h2>Deepening Your Practice</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Breathe Mindfully</h3>
              <p>The breath is at the core of yoga practice. Focus on deep, steady breathing to enhance the benefits of your practice and stay present.</p>
              <p>If you find yourself holding your breath or breathing shallowly, it may be a sign to back off or modify a pose.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Practice With Intention</h3>
              <p>Set an intention at the beginning of each practice. This could be a quality you want to cultivate, a dedication, or simply an area of focus.</p>
              <p>Return to your intention throughout your practice, especially when challenges arise.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Move Beyond Asana</h3>
              <p>Explore other aspects of yoga beyond the physical poses, such as meditation, pranayama (breathing techniques), and yogic philosophy.</p>
              <p>These practices can deepen your understanding and enhance the benefits of your physical practice.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Study Alignment</h3>
              <p>Deepen your knowledge of proper alignment in each pose. Small adjustments can transform your experience and prevent injury.</p>
              <p>Consider workshops or private sessions to refine your understanding of key poses.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Keep a Practice Journal</h3>
              <p>Record your experiences, insights, and challenges. Note how different practices affect your body, mind, and energy levels.</p>
              <p>Reviewing your journal can reveal patterns and progress that might otherwise go unnoticed.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Challenge Yourself Wisely</h3>
              <p>Step outside your comfort zone occasionally, but with awareness and respect for your body's limits.</p>
              <p>Growth happens at the edge of comfort, but pushing too far can lead to injury or burnout.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-content-box" id="mindset-content">
          <h2>Mindset & Approach</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Practice Non-Judgment</h3>
              <p>Approach your practice with curiosity rather than judgment. Notice sensations, thoughts, and emotions without labeling them as good or bad.</p>
              <p>This mindset of acceptance can transform your practice and extend into daily life.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Focus on Progress, Not Perfection</h3>
              <p>Celebrate small improvements rather than fixating on achieving "perfect" poses. Yoga is a lifelong journey, not a destination.</p>
              <p>Remember that even experienced practitioners continue to learn and grow.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Stay Present</h3>
              <p>When your mind wanders (and it will), gently bring your attention back to your breath and the sensations in your body.</p>
              <p>Each return to presence is a moment of practice, not a failure of focus.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Practice Gratitude</h3>
              <p>Cultivate appreciation for what your body can do, rather than focusing on limitations. Thank yourself for showing up on your mat.</p>
              <p>End your practice with a moment of gratitude for the opportunity to practice and grow.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Let Go of Comparisons</h3>
              <p>Avoid comparing yourself to others in class or on social media. Your yoga journey is uniquely yours.</p>
              <p>The person who can touch their toes may struggle with balance poses that come easily to you.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Embrace Consistency Over Intensity</h3>
              <p>A gentle practice done regularly yields more benefits than occasional intense sessions.</p>
              <p>Honor where you are each day, adjusting your practice to meet your current needs and energy levels.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-content-box" id="props-content">
          <h2>Using Props Effectively</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Use Props When Needed</h3>
              <p>Yoga props like blocks, straps, and bolsters are not just for beginners—they're tools that can help practitioners of all levels access poses safely.</p>
              <p>Props can help you maintain proper alignment and get the full benefit of a pose while respecting your body's limitations.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Blocks for Support</h3>
              <p>Use blocks to "bring the floor closer" in standing forward folds or to support hands in poses like Triangle or Half Moon.</p>
              <p>Blocks can also support seated poses, helping to maintain proper spinal alignment when tight hips make sitting on the floor challenging.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Straps for Extension</h3>
              <p>Straps can effectively extend your reach in poses where flexibility is limited, such as forward folds or shoulder stretches.</p>
              <p>Loop a strap around your feet in seated forward folds or reclined hand-to-big-toe pose to maintain proper alignment while working on flexibility.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Bolsters for Restoration</h3>
              <p>Bolsters provide comfortable support in restorative poses, allowing for complete relaxation and release.</p>
              <p>Place a bolster under your spine for a gentle heart opener, or between your thighs in reclined bound angle pose for hip support.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Blankets for Comfort</h3>
              <p>Folded blankets can cushion knees in kneeling poses, support the sit bones in seated positions, or provide warmth during final relaxation.</p>
              <p>A rolled blanket under the neck in Savasana can help release neck tension and support proper cervical alignment.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Create a Dedicated Space</h3>
              <p>Designate a specific area for your practice, even if it's just enough room for your mat. Having a consistent space helps establish a routine.</p>
              <p>Keep your space clean, uncluttered, and free from distractions to help maintain focus during your practice.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
